# Isaac Sim MCP Rules

# General Rules
- Before executing any code, always check if the scene is properly initialized by calling get_scene_info()
- When working with robots, try using create_robot() first before using execute_script()
- If execute_script() fails due to communication error, retry up to 3 times at most
- For any creation of robot, call create_physics_scene() first
- Always print the formatted code into chat to confirm before execution

# Physics Rules
- If the scene is empty, create a physics scene with create_physics_scene()
- For physics simulation, avoid using simulation_context to run simulations in the main thread
- Use the World class with async methods for initializing physics and running simulations
- When needed, use my_world.play() followed by multiple step_async() calls to wait for physics to stabilize
- SingleArticulation.initialize() requires World.physics_sim_view to be non-None.
  The adapter's play() and create_action_graph() call _ensure_physics_world() to guarantee this.
  When user presses Play from UI, the script must do its own World + initialize_physics() in a warmup phase.

# Robot Creation Rules
- Before creating a robot, verify availability of connection with get_scene_info()
- Available robot types: "franka", "frankafr3", "jetbot", "carter", "g1", "go1" (use list_available_robots for full list)
- Position robots using their appropriate parameters
- For custom robot configurations, use execute_script() only when create_robot() is insufficient

# Physics Scene Rules
- Objects should include 'type' and 'position' at minimum
- Object format example: {"path": "/World/Cube", "type": "Cube", "size": 20, "position": [0, 100, 0]}
- Default gravity is [0, 0, -981.0] (cm/s^2)
- Set floor=True to create a default ground plane

# Script Execution Rules
- Use World class instead of SimulationContext when possible
- Initialize physics before trying to control any articulations
- When controlling robots, make sure to step the physics at least once before interaction
- For robot joint control, first initialize the articulation, then get the controller

# ScriptNode Script Rules (CRITICAL)
#
# ALWAYS define setup(db) and compute(db) functions. This is the "proper" mode
# where module-level globals, function definitions, and list comprehensions
# all work correctly.
#
# Structure:
#   - Module-level globals for persistent state (_robot = None, _state = "IDLE")
#   - setup(db): runs once, subscribe to timeline STOP to reset state
#   - compute(db): runs every tick, use `global` keyword for mutable state
#   - _on_tl(event): reset globals on TimelineEventType.STOP so next Play re-inits
#
# Physics init inside compute():
#   - Use a WARMUP state (skip first ~30 frames) before calling World.initialize_physics()
#   - This ensures physics is ready even when user presses Play from Isaac Sim UI
#   - Pattern: _world = World.instance() or World(...); _world.initialize_physics()
#
# DO NOT use "legacy mode" (no compute(db) function). Legacy mode runs the entire
# script via exec() each tick, causing:
#   - Variables lost every tick (go into compute() locals, not module globals)
#   - Function defs can't access exec locals (__globals__ mismatch)
#   - List comprehensions can't access exec locals (Python 3 scoping)
# If you must use legacy mode, store ALL state in builtins._my_data dict.

